      "text": "The current visualization uses a JSON dataset of cities to create an \"impressionistic\" map. By plotting individual city coordinates, the canvas renders a scattered pattern of red dots that roughly outline the contiguous 48 US states.\n\n### Data Normalization and Bounds\nTo map geographic coordinates (latitude and longitude) onto a digital canvas, we must first determine the boundaries of our dataset. We do this by iterating through the data to find the minimum and maximum values for both axes. This \"bounding box\" is essential for translating real-world coordinates into local pixel values.\n\nThe following code demonstrates how to load a JSON file and calculate these bounds:\n\n```javascript\n// Cities JSON \n// https://gist.github.com/Miserlou/c5cd8364bf9b2420bb29\nlet cities;\n\n// Initialize bounds with extreme values to ensure any data point \n// will correctly expand the range during iteration.\nlet minLat = 90;\nlet maxLat = -90;\nlet minLong = 180;\nlet maxLong = -180;\n\nfunction preload() {\n  // Asynchronously load the JSON data before setup runs\n  loadJSON(\"assets/cities.json\", onLoad, onError);\n}\n\nfunction setup() {\n  createCanvas(500, 400);\n  console.log({cities});\n\n  // Iterate through the array of city objects to find data extremes\n  for (let city of cities) {\n    if (city.latitude < minLat) {\n      minLat = city.latitude;\n    }\n    if (city.latitude > maxLat) {\n      maxLat = city.latitude;\n    }\n    if (city.longitude < minLong) {\n      minLong = city.longitude;\n    }\n    if (city.longitude > maxLong) {\n      maxLong = city.longitude;\n    }\n  }\n}\n```",
      "heading": "Visualizing Points with JSON",
